Great question! This is a much better approach for certificate lifecycle management. Let me explain the options:

------

## Recommendation: Option 2 — Runner Volume Mount

This is the cleanest solution for your air-gapped setup. Here's exactly how to implement it:

### Step 1 — Place the cert on the runner host

```bash
# On the GitLab runner host machine
sudo mkdir -p /etc/gitlab-runner/certs
sudo cp jfrog-chain.crt /etc/gitlab-runner/certs/jfrog-chain.crt
sudo chmod 644 /etc/gitlab-runner/certs/jfrog-chain.crt
```

---

### Step 2 — Mount it into build containers via `config.toml`

Edit `/etc/gitlab-runner/config.toml` on the runner:

```toml
[[runners]]
  name = "sbiepay-runner"
  executor = "docker"
  [runners.docker]
    image = "registry.dev.sbiepay.sbi:8443/gradle:9.3.0-jdk21"
    volumes = [
      "/cache",
      "/etc/gitlab-runner/certs/jfrog-chain.crt:/tmp/jfrog-chain.crt:ro"   # <-- add this
    ]
```

> `:ro` = read-only mount. The cert is visible inside every build container at `/tmp/jfrog-chain.crt`.

---

### Step 3 — Remove cert from Dockerfile, import it in CI job instead

**Updated Dockerfile** — cert completely removed:

```dockerfile
FROM registry.dev.sbiepay.sbi:8443/ubi9/openjdk-21:1.24-2.1776357031

ENV GRADLE_VERSION=9.3.0 \
    GRADLE_HOME=/opt/gradle \
    GRADLE_USER_HOME=/home/gradle/.gradle \
    PATH=/opt/gradle/bin:$PATH

USER root
COPY gradle-9.3.0/ /opt/gradle-9.3.0/
RUN ln -s /opt/gradle-9.3.0 /opt/gradle \
    && chmod +x /opt/gradle-9.3.0/bin/gradle \
    && useradd -u 1001 -m -s /bin/bash gradle \
    && mkdir -p /home/gradle/.gradle \
    && chown -R gradle:gradle /home/gradle /opt/gradle-9.3.0 /opt/gradle

USER gradle
WORKDIR /workspace
CMD ["gradle", "--version"]
```

**`.gitlab-ci.yml`** — import cert at job start:

```yaml
before_script:
  - keytool -import
      -trustcacerts
      -file /tmp/jfrog-chain.crt
      -keystore $JAVA_HOME/lib/security/cacerts
      -alias SBI-INTERNAL
      -storepass changeit
      -noprompt
```

---

### When the cert rotates (every 6–12 months)

```bash
# Only this — nothing else changes
sudo cp new-jfrog-chain.crt /etc/gitlab-runner/certs/jfrog-chain.crt
```

No image rebuild. No pipeline changes. No GitLab UI changes. Just replace the file on the runner host and the next job picks it up automatically.
